\f0\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 Material
\f1\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi944\sl640\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 Ninety items were selected, including 72 common objects (saw, apron, envelope...) and 18 vegetables (carrot, cauliflower, onion...).\'a0 Participants were presented with either the mere verbal label of the item or the picture of the item along with its verbal label.\'a0 Half of the items were presented as single words and the other half as word/picture pairs.\'a0 Two versions of the stimuli were prepared; the 45 stimuli that were presented as words in one version were presented as word/picture pairs in the other.\'a0 The use of each version was counterbalanced among subjects.\'a0 All material was presented to participants throughout via Presentation ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.neurobs.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 http://www.neurobs.com/}}).\'a0 Before both the encoding and the recall phases, participants were administered a few practice trials to ensure familiarity with the task.
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl640\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\i\b\fs32 \cf2 \'a0
\f1\i0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl853\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf2 Procedure
\f1\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl746\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs37\fsmilli18667 \cf2 Encoding
\f1\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi944\sl640\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 All items were presented one by one in pseudo-random order with each slide (word or word/picture pair) being presented for 3.5 seconds, separated by fixation crosses.\'a0 The stimulus onset asynchrony varied across trials from 5.5 to 9 seconds according to an exponential distribution with a mean of 6.68 seconds.\'a0 The encoding of the items was implicit since the task was described as a classification task: participants were required to indicate whether the presented items were vegetables or not, and to give their response by pressing one of two buttons (\'91vegetable\'92 or \'91other\'92).\'a0 They were not informed of the subsequent recall task.\'a0 The computer recorded correct and incorrect responses, as well as misses (i.e., no response after 2 seconds from the end of the stimulus).
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \

\f0\fs32 \'a0
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl746\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs37\fsmilli18667 \cf2 Recall
\f1\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi944\sl640\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 A 6-minute delay followed, during which a structural MRI scan was acquired for each participant.\'a0 Then the participants were informed that they would be presented with all the labels of the stimuli they had previously seen, and that they would have to remember whether a picture accompanied the item at the encoding phase.\'a0 The labels were presented one at a time for a 3.5-second period, in pseudo-random order different from that used in the encoding stage, but with similar stimulus onset asynchrony distribution.\'a0 After the appearance of each label the participants were asked to provide their response by pressing one of two buttons (\'91with picture\'92 or \'91without picture\'92).\'a0 The correct responses, i.e., presented words remembered as words (WW) and presented pictures remembered as pictures (PP), were recorded, as were the incorrect responses: the omissions, i.e. presented pictures remembered as words (PW) and the false memories of pictures, i.e. presented words remembered as pictures (WP).\'a0 Again, missed trials were recorded. \'a0
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \

\f0\fs32 \'a0
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \

\f0\fs32 The response times for each type of response were recorded as well.\'a0 Prior to the experimental protocol participants were provided with an opportunity to ask any questions they had.
