\f0\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf2 fMRI data acquisition
\f1\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi944\sl512\sa0\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Functional MRI data were acquired with a 1.5T General Electric Signa HDe scanner at Parc Sanitari Sant Joan de D\'e9u.\'a0 A T2*-weighted functional echoplanar imaging sequence depicting BOLD contrast was obtained using a quadrature head coil. In total 270 volumes were collected with slices parallel to the AC-PC plane, resulting in an axial-oblique orientation.\'a0 The following scanning parameters were used: 26 slices, 4\'a0mm thickness, 1 mm gap, TR\'a0=\'a02000\'a0ms, TE\'a0=\'a040\'a0ms, 24 cm FOV, 64 \'d7 64 acquisition matrix, flip angle\'a0=\'a090\'b0. \'a0The first seven volumes in each run were discarded to allow for magnetic saturation effects.\'a0 Visual stimuli were presented on a rear projection screen and viewed through a mirror mounted on the head coil, and all responses were collected with an MR-compatible response box (fORP,\'a0Current Designs, Inc., USA; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.curdes.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 \strokec5 www.curdes.com}}). \
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl853\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf2 fMRI data preprocessing
\f1\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi944\sl640\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 Imaging data were analyzed using SPM8 (Wellcome Department of Imaging Neuroscience, London; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.fil.ion.ucl.ac.uk/spm"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 \strokec5 www.fil.ion.ucl.ac.uk/spm}}) running under MATLAB (Release 2009a, The MathWorks, Inc., Natick, Massachusetts).\'a0 All of the volumes from each participant were spatially realigned to the first image in each series, in order to correct for small head movements and to generate a mean image for the functional series. Motion parameters were examined for each subject to ensure no movements larger than the voxel size were present (no runs were discarded).\'a0 The resulting series were transformed into SRI24 space [22], with a standard EPI template as deformation target, and then spatially smoothed using a Gaussian kernel of 8 mm full-width-at-half-maximum.
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \

\f0\fs32 Due to machine errors, data from the encoding task for one participant (from the low imagery subgroup) were disregarded, as were data from the recall task for two other participants (both among the ten participants excluded from the high- vs. low-imagery subgroups).
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \

\f0\fs32 \'a0
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl853\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf2 fMRI data analysis
\f1\b0\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl640\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Preprocessed fMRI data were then analyzed with an event-related model, using SPM8.\'a0 In order to assess random effects at the individual level, the activity associated with the experimental conditions was modeled with a hemodynamic response function (HRF).\'a0 To control for slice timing discrepancies we also included the time derivative of the HRF in the model.\'a0 Displacement and rotation motion parameters were included as confounds in the individual model.\'a0 A 200 s high-pass filter cut-off was used to remove low frequency noise, together with an AR(1) model to correct for temporal autocorrelation.\'a0 
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi944\sl640\sa0\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 For both tasks, four event types were determined by the responses in the recall task: WW, PP, PW, and WP.\'a0 To compare each event, linear contrasts were constructed to test experimental effects of interest.\'a0 These contrasts were entered into a second level analysis in which subjects were treated as a random effect. \'a0One-sample and two- sample t-tests were used to assess within-group and between-subgroup activations, respectively. 
\f1\fs25\fsmilli12800 \

\f0\fs32 The resulting statistical parametric maps were generated with SPM8, initially using an uncorrected voxel-level threshold defined by T = 3.0 (p < 0.003) and a cluster extent threshold defined by a family-wise-error (FWE) corrected p
\fs26\fsmilli13333 \sub  
\fs32 \nosupersub < 0.05. \'a0In the event that the resulting activation clusters encompassed several brain structures, a more restrictive voxel-wise threshold, T = 3.8\'964.0 (p < 0.0004), was applied to better identify local activation maxima in each brain structure, again followed by a p < 0.05 FWE-corrected threshold on the remaining clusters.\'a0 Activation peaks were labeled according to the SRI24/TZO cortical parcellation map [22] based on the template described by Tzourio-Mazoyer et al. [23].
